INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '2e98d0f8-429c-4d11-a05f-1c53bda91192',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$GCP IAM — Least Privilege with Service Accounts and Predefined Roles$escape$,
  $escape$Every workload on GCP should run as a dedicated service account, never as a user account and never as the default compute service account (which has Editor on the entire project). Create purpose-built service accounts with the minimum predefined role needed — or custom roles if predefined ones are too broad.

Binding happens at the resource level, not just the project level. Attach roles to a Cloud Run service, a GCS bucket, or a Pub/Sub topic directly using `gcloud ... add-iam-policy-binding` with `--member=serviceAccount:...`. This scopes blast radius: a compromised Cloud Run SA can't touch your BigQuery datasets if the binding was never made.

Avoid primitive roles (`roles/owner`, `roles/editor`, `roles/viewer`) entirely — they're legacy and overly broad. Prefer `roles/run.invoker`, `roles/storage.objectViewer`, `roles/pubsub.publisher`, etc. Use `gcloud iam roles describe` to audit permissions before assigning. Rotate keys aggressively or, better, use Workload Identity Federation to eliminate key files altogether.$escape$,
  $escape$# Create a least-privilege service account for a Cloud Run job
gcloud iam service-accounts create etl-job-sa \
  --display-name="ETL Job Service Account" \
  --project=my-project

# Grant only the permissions it needs — at the bucket level, not project
gcloud storage buckets add-iam-policy-binding gs://my-data-bucket \
  --member="serviceAccount:etl-job-sa@my-project.iam.gserviceaccount.com" \
  --role="roles/storage.objectViewer"

# Bind the SA to the Cloud Run service (not the default compute SA)
gcloud run services update etl-service \
  --service-account=etl-job-sa@my-project.iam.gserviceaccount.com \
  --region=us-central1$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
