INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '0588435e-e6c8-4138-a531-fc9eb86b5f6f',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$GCP Vendor Lock-in — Where Portability Dies and Where It Survives$escape$,
  $escape$GCP's managed services sit on a portability spectrum. Cloud Run containers and GKE workloads are genuinely portable — your image runs on any OCI-compliant runtime. Cloud Storage supports S3-compatible HMAC auth, making it interchangeable at the SDK level. But go one layer deeper and the abstraction breaks: `google_spanner_instance` in Terraform abstracts syntax, not semantics — there's no AWS equivalent to point the same config at.

The hard lock-in lives in analytics and ML: BigQuery's columnar engine, Dataflow jobs wired to Pub/Sub via `apache_beam.io.ReadFromPubSub`, and Vertex AI Feature Store have no drop-in cross-cloud replacements. Abstracting these behind a repository interface helps unit testing but won't survive a cloud migration.

Anthos extends GKE's control plane to AWS and on-prem, but management still routes through GCP — it's operational portability, not financial independence. For auth, prefer Workload Identity Federation over service account keys; OIDC tokens are cloud-portable, JSON key files are not.

Pragmatic rule: accept lock-in on BigQuery and Pub/Sub where GCP's operational cost justifies it, keep compute on Cloud Run, and document every `google_*` Terraform resource as a migration cost line item.$escape$,
  $escape$resource "google_cloud_run_v2_service" "api" {
  name     = "byte-api"
  location = "us-central1"

  template {
    service_account = google_service_account.api_sa.email
    containers {
      image = "us-central1-docker.pkg.dev/${var.project_id}/repo/api:latest"
      env {
        name  = "DB_URL"
        value_source {
          secret_key_ref {
            secret  = google_secret_manager_secret.db_url.secret_id
            version = "latest"
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
